  "prompt": "What are the various Incarnations of Lord Vishnu and what is going to be the last Incarnation of Lord Vishnu?",
  "response": "Lord Vishnu is believed to incarnate (avatara) whenever there's a significant imbalance of dharma (righteousness) in the world. The most commonly recognized list of his incarnations is the **Dashavatara**, which consists of ten major avatars. However, many other incarnations are mentioned in Hindu scriptures.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n**The Dashavatara (Ten Major Incarnations):**\n\n1.  **Matsya (Fish):**  Appears during a great flood to save Manu (the progenitor of mankind), the Vedas, and important seeds/herbs. Symbolizes guidance and preservation through chaos.\n2.  **Kurma (Tortoise):**  Supports Mount Mandara as the gods and demons churn the ocean of milk to obtain Amrita (the elixir of immortality). Represents stability, perseverance, and cooperation.\n3.  **Varaha (Boar):**  Kills the demon Hiranyaksha, who had dragged the Earth to the bottom of the cosmic ocean, and restores the Earth to its proper place. Symbolizes strength, rescue, and the re-establishment of order.\n4.  **Narasimha (Man-Lion):**  Emerges from a pillar to slay the demon Hiranyakashipu, who had obtained a boon making him virtually invulnerable.  Saves his devotee, Prahlada.  Represents the triumph of good over evil, divine justice, and protection of devotees.\n5.  **Vamana (Dwarf):**  Appears as a dwarf Brahmin to the demon king Bali, who had conquered the three worlds.  Vamana requests three paces of land. With his first two steps, he covers the Earth and the heavens.  Unable to fulfill his promise, Bali offers his head for the third step. Vishnu then sends Bali to the netherworld (Patala). Represents humility, divine strategy, and restoring balance of power.\n6.  **Parashurama (Axe-Wielding Warrior):**  A Brahmin warrior who avenges his father's death by destroying the tyrannical Kshatriya (warrior) caste multiple times.  Symbolizes righteousness, retribution against injustice, and the restoration of social order.\n7.  **Rama (Prince of Ayodhya):**  The hero of the Ramayana, known for his adherence to dharma, his unwavering loyalty, and his victory over the demon king Ravana.  Represents ideal kingship, righteousness, and the power of good to overcome evil.\n8.  **Krishna (Prince of Dwarka):**  A central figure in the Mahabharata.  Known for his wisdom, his role as a charioteer for Arjuna, and his teachings in the Bhagavad Gita. Represents divine wisdom, leadership, and the guiding force in the cosmic order.\n9.  **Buddha (The Enlightened One):**  This is a somewhat controversial inclusion. Some Hindu schools of thought consider Buddha an incarnation of Vishnu, intended to end animal sacrifices and promote compassion. Others reject this view. Represents compassion, non-violence, and a departure from traditional Vedic rituals (in some interpretations).  Note that this is not the same as *the* Buddha revered in Buddhism.\n10. **Kalki (The Destroyer of Filth):**  This is the *future* incarnation.\n\n**Kalki: The Final Incarnation**\n\nKalki is the prophesied tenth and final avatar of Vishnu, who is expected to appear at the end of Kali Yuga (the current epoch, considered the age of darkness and degradation). According to predictions:\n\n*   **Time of Arrival:** Kalki will appear at the end of the Kali Yuga, a time when righteousness has all but vanished, and corruption, violence, and moral decay are rampant.\n*   **Appearance:** He is often depicted as a warrior riding a white horse named Devadatta, wielding a blazing sword.\n*   **Purpose:** Kalki's purpose is to destroy the wicked, restore dharma, and usher in a new Satya Yuga (the age of truth and righteousness). He will cleanse the earth of evil and re-establish the principles of virtue, justice, and peace.\n*   **Lineage:** He will be born into a Brahmin family in the village of Shambhala. His parents' names are often given as Vishnuyasha (father) and Sumati (mother).\n\n**Other Incarnations of Vishnu:**\n\nBeyond the Dashavatara, many other incarnations are mentioned in various Puranas and other scriptures. Some notable examples include:\n\n*   **Hayagriva:**  An avatar with a horse's head, who retrieved the Vedas stolen by demons.\n*   **Dhanvantari:** The physician of the gods, who appeared during the churning of the ocean of milk, carrying the pot of Amrita.\n*   **Mohini:** A female form Vishnu assumed to trick the demons out of the Amrita.\n*   **Yajna:**  An incarnation of Vishnu representing sacrifice.\n*   **Dattatreya:** A sage considered an avatar of the Trimurti (Brahma, Vishnu, Shiva).\n*   **Rishabha:** The first Jain Tirthankara is considered by some to be an avatara of Vishnu.\n\n**Key Takeaways:**\n\n*   The Dashavatara are the most commonly recognized avatars of Vishnu.\n*   Kalki is the predicted final incarnation, who will appear at the end of Kali Yuga to restore dharma.\n*   Many other avatars are mentioned in Hindu texts, reflecting the multifaceted nature of Vishnu and his role in maintaining cosmic order.\n*   Each avatar has a specific purpose and teaches a particular lesson.\n*   The concept of avatars reinforces the Hindu belief that God intervenes in the world to protect dharma and guide humanity.\n\nThe accounts of the avatars can vary across different scriptures and traditions. Understanding these variations adds to the richness and complexity of Hindu mythology.\n",
